<section class="proof-section" id="proof">
  <div class="proof-section__inner page-width">
    <p class="proof-section__eyebrow">The research</p>
    <h2 class="proof-section__headline display-md">
      Three facts that changed how we think about women's supplementation.
    </h2>

    <div class="proof-section__grid">
      <div class="proof-card">
        <span class="proof-card__num">01</span>
        <p class="proof-card__stat">+22% upper-body strength</p>
        <p class="proof-card__detail">
          Women 57–70 taking 5g creatine daily for 12 weeks gained significantly more strength than placebo — without resistance training.
        </p>
        <p class="proof-card__citation">Candow et al., 2019</p>
      </div>

      <div class="proof-card">
        <span class="proof-card__num">02</span>
        <p class="proof-card__stat">68% lower depression risk</p>
        <p class="proof-card__detail">
          Creatine supplementation in women with MDD reduced depressive symptoms in 2 weeks. Brain energy metabolism is the proposed mechanism.
        </p>
        <p class="proof-card__citation">Yoon et al., 2016</p>
      </div>

      <div class="proof-card">
        <span class="proof-card__num">03</span>
        <p class="proof-card__stat">45% of women are deficient</p>
        <p class="proof-card__detail">
          Nearly half of adult women don't meet the RDA for magnesium. Glycinate is the most bioavailable form without the digestive side effects of oxide.
        </p>
        <p class="proof-card__citation">NHANES, 2020–2021</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

